al Seminary — graduated and ordained 1861 as Congregational minister."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Founded Florida's first college after moving south","body":"He moved from his Massachusetts parish to Winter Park, Florida in 1883 seeking better health. Within two years he was charter trustee, pastor, and first president of Rollins College — Florida's first recognized institution of higher learning."},{"number":2,"category":"social_reform","header":"Championed Seminole education in early Florida","body":"As Rollins president he advocated for educational equity for Florida's Seminole population and worked to raise overall regional standards. He personally housed students in financial difficulty in his own home."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Survived an 1893 hurricane shipwreck refusing rescue","body":"In 1893 he survived the wreck of the steamship City of Savannah, disabled by a hurricane and grounded off Fripp Island. He led prayer services on the wreck and refused rescue until others were safe; injuries from the ordeal contributed to his decline."},{"number":4,"category":"education","header":"Replaced exams with daily classroom participation","body":"At Rollins he introduced daily classroom participation in place of traditional examinations. He also established the gymnasium and physical education curriculum — innovations for an 1880s American college."},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"Hooker Hall at Rollins commemorates his founding role","body":"The 1937 Mediterranean-style Hooker Hall — designed by Kiehnel and Elliott — bears his name. The Hooker Educational Building at Rollins College also commemorates his role as founding president (1885-1892)."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"HD1326","display_label":"Capt. Russell died fighting Seminoles fifty years earlier","link_text":"Capt. Samuel Law Russell","description":"Capt. Samuel Law Russell was killed fighting in the Second Seminole War in 1839. Roughly fifty years later, his distant cousin Rev. Edward Payson Hooker became founding president of Rollins College in Florida and was a vocal advocate for Seminole education and educational equity — a remarkable arc within one Hooker descent line."},{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD6189","display_label":"also a Hooker-descended minister who led a college"}],"career":[{"role":"Congregational minister","organization":"Massachusetts and Vermont parishes","start_year":1861,"end_year":1883,"notes":"Ordained 1861 after graduating Andover Theological Seminary."},{"role":"Charter trustee + College pastor + First President","organization":"Rollins College, Winter Park FL","start_year":1885,"end_year":1892,"notes":"Drove the founding of Rollins College — Florida's first recognized institution of higher learning. Taught philosophy, ethics, logic, and the Bible. Introduced progressive academic practices including daily classroom participation in place of traditional exams. Established the school's gymnasium and physical education curriculum. Personally housed students in financial difficulty. Resigned 1892."},{"role":"Advocate for Seminole education + regional educational standards","organization":"Florida","start_year":1885,"end_year":1898,"notes":"Advocated for better learning opportunities for the Seminole population and worked to raise overall educational standards in the region."},{"role":"Active community minister and educator (post-presidency)","organization":"Florida + post-1898 retirement","start_year":1892,"end_year":1898,"notes":"Continued community service after Rollins. Survived 1893 wreck of City of Savannah; injuries led to declining health and 1898 retirement."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Rev. Edward Payson Hooker","first_name":"Edward","last_name":"Hooker","title":"Reverend","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://scholarship.rollins.edu/presidents/1013/thumbnail.jpg"},"landmarks":[{"landmark_id":"LM051","landmark_blurb":"Buil